content:
Introduce Object Search in a Dialog (Beta)

Deliver records from standard or custom objects to your Einstein Bot to create an integrated bot experience. Using a Question dialog step and an Action dialog step, the bot can deliver one, two, or three records that match the end user’s search criteria.

REQUIRED EDITIONS AND USER PERMISSIONS
Einstein Bots is available in Salesforce Classic and Lightning Experience. Setup for Einstein Bots is available in Lightning Experience.
Available in: Enterprise, Performance, Unlimited, and Developer Editions

USER PERMISSIONS NEEDED
To build and manage Einstein Bots:
Customize Application
OR
Modify Metadata
OR
Manage Bots

To employ object search, the Bot User must be assigned to a Custom Chatbot User with access to the object. To change the Bot User, visit the Bot Overview page.

Object Search supports the following standard objects: Account, Case, Contact, Campaign, Contract, Knowledge, Lead, Opportunity, Order, Task
Object Search supports the following standard field types: Auto-Number, Birthday, Boolean, Content, Currency (including Currency ISO Code), Date, DateTime, Double, Due Date, Email, Entity ID, Enums (dynamic, static), Fax, Integer, Long, Multi-line Text, Percent, Phone Number, Record Type, String Plus Clob (text only), Text, URL
NOTE Object Search doesn’t support rich text, long text, or text area field types.

From the Dialog Component Library, drag a step from the Questions section onto the canvas. In the Step Properties panel, enter the question from your bot to the customer.
Drag the Object Search action step onto the canvas. In the Step Properties panel, select your object for the Object field.
In the Results section, specify your delivery options. The bot can return up to three records and up to three fields for each record.
In the Search Results Variable field, select an object list variable for the bot to store the results.

To tell the bot what to do in case it doesn’t find any results, from the Dialog Component Library, drag the Redirect to Dialog step onto the canvas. In the Step Properties panel, set the condition to check if the number of results in the search results variable is less than one.
Add a friendly message before the redirect using Send a Message Rule Action.

To deliver the results to the end user, add a Question dialog step. In the Step Properties panel, enter a message. Select an object list variable to save the selection.
To expand the choice selection, change the Choice Type to Dynamic and identify the field that is placed within the choice buttons using merge syntax.

To call a specific record or article, use FieldName[X], with X referring to the location of the item in the list.

In the Action Type field, select From List Variable. In the Input (List Variable) field, select the Object list variable used as the result variable.
Set a Backup Rule to redirect to the Confused dialog if no results are found.

To deliver the contents of the record or article to the customer, add a Message dialog step and include the field names using merge syntax.
title: Introducing Object Search in Einstein Bots
